This paper is about improving the efficiency of deep neural network architectures through evolutionary synthesis. The primary focus is on neural networks, which suggests that the most likely sub-category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of deep learning techniques and the MNIST and CIFAR-10 datasets, which are commonly used in computer vision research, suggesting that cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is also a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of evolutionary algorithms, which suggests that cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) are also possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of the proposed method in robotics, which suggests that cs.SY (Systems and Control) is a less likely but still possible sub-category.
